      "\n  | left  : P ŌåÆ Disjunction P Q\n  | right : Q ŌåÆ Disjunction P Q\n\nopen Disjunction\nexample\n    (rec : ŌłĆ (P Q : Prop) (motive : Disjunction P Q ŌåÆ Type)\n      (h_left : ŌłĆ hp : P, motive (Disjunction.left P Q hp)) (h_right : ŌłĆ hq : Q, motive (Disjunction.right P Q hq))\n      (h : Disjunction P Q), motive h)\n    (comp_left : ŌłĆ P Q motive h_left h_right (hp : P),\n      rec P Q motive h_left h_right (Disjunction.left P Q hp) = h_left hp)\n    (comp_right : ŌłĆ P Q motive h_left h_right (hq : Q),\n      rec P Q motive h_left h_right (Disjunction.right P Q hq) = h_right hq) : False := by\n```\n\nNow, we need to apply `rec` with a specific set of arguments to derive `False`.\n\nLet's pick `P := True` and `Q := True`. Then `h := Disjunction.left P Q (by trivial)` is a proof of `True Ōł© True`, which is `True`.\n\nThen `h_left := fun hp : True => False.elim (by simp at hp)` is a function that takes a proof of `True` and returns a proof of `False`. Similarly for `h_right`.\n\nThen `rec P Q (fun _ => False) h_left h_right h` will apply `rec` to the proposition `True` with a motive `fun _ => False`. `h_left` and `h_right` will convert any proof of `True` into a proof of `False`. `h` is `True`. So `rec` will prove `False`.\n\nSo, the proof is:\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 := rec True True (fun _ => False) (fun hp => False.elim (by simp at hp)) (fun hq => False.elim (by simp at hq)) (Or.inl (by trivial))\n```\n\nWait, this is getting complex. Let's try to simplify.\n\nWait, `P := True`, `Q := True`. `h := Or.inl (by trivial)`. `h_left := fun hp => False.elim (by simp at hp)`. `h_right := fun hq => False.elim (by simp at hq)`. The motive is `fun _ => False`.\n\nSo, `h1` will be `False`. Then we can use `h1` to prove `False`.\n\nSo, the final proof is:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathli